{{multiple image | align = right | perrow = 1 | width = 270 | image1 = Ursula (detention center) 1.png | caption1 = Separated family members detained in cages | image2 = Texas Photo 1.jpg | caption2 = Detained children lying on matresses within a caged area | footer = Photos provided by Custom and Border Protection to reporter on tour of Ursala detention facility in McAllen, Texas. Reporters were not allowed to take their own photos. }} '''Ursula''' is the colloquial name of the largest [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] detention center for undocumented immigrants. It was opened in 2014 on W. Ursula Avenue in [[McAllen, Texas]]. In June 2018, it gained notoriety for the practice of keeping children in large [[cage]]s made of [[chain-link fencing]].<ref name=":1"/><ref name=Frej/>
== About == The center, better known as "Ursula," is the largest immigration processing and detention center run by the [[United States Border Patrol|Border Patrol]] and the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|Customs and Border Protection Agency]].<ref name=":1" /> The detention and processing center was opened in 2014 at 3700 W. Ursula Avenue in McAllen, Texas.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.themonitor.com/news/local/article_b22a23ae-0e2b-11e4-b9d3-0017a43b2370.html|title=Border Patrol opens central processing facility for unaccompanied kids|last=Findell|first=Elizabeth|date=17 July 2014|work=The Monitor|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref> The facility is made from a former [[warehouse]] which was leased by the federal government and modified to be able to hold 1,000 children.<ref name=":0" /> Children are kept in cages made of [[chain-link fencing]] inside of the 77,000 square-foot warehouse.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/06/inside-ursula-border-patrol-center-family-separation.html|title=Inside 3 Detention Centers Where Immigrant Children Are Kept From Their Parents|last=Ryan|first=Lisa|date=18 June 2018|work=The Cut|access-date=2018-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618222337/https://www.thecut.com/2018/06/inside-ursula-border-patrol-center-family-separation.html|archive-date=18 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>
Minors who arrive at the [[Mexico–United States border]] unaccompanied or who have been separated from their families are supposed to only stay in this type of processing center for under 72 hours.<ref name=":1" /> After processing, minors are sent to facilities run by the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]].<ref name=Frej>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/images-inside-center-immigrants_us_5b27bebae4b0f9178a9f6f7f|title=These Are The Texas Immigration Center Photos Stirring Anti-Trump Outrage|last=Frej|first=Willa|date=2018-06-18|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618224954/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/images-inside-center-immigrants_us_5b27bebae4b0f9178a9f6f7f|archive-date=18 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The facility also houses adults and individuals are separated based on how they crossed into the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mcallen-texas-immigration-facility-separated-families-today-2018-06-18/|title=Inside the Texas facility housing hundreds of illegal immigrants|last=Begnaud|first=David|date=18 June 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=2018-06-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619001212/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mcallen-texas-immigration-facility-separated-families-today-2018-06-18/|archive-date=18 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>
Filming or photography is not allowed inside of the facility.<ref name=":1" /> During the weekend of June 16, 2018, reporters were allowed to tour the facility (without cameras).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/national-international/Children-Border-Patrol-Facility-South-Texas-485804601.html|title=Kids in Cages With Mylar Blankets in Texas Border Facility|last=Ciechalski|first=Suzanne|date=18 June 2018|work=NBC Chicago|access-date=2018-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618225301/https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/national-international/Children-Border-Patrol-Facility-South-Texas-485804601.html|archive-date=18 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>
